04096nam a22006375i 9780226489711DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264897117 a10.7208/97802264897112doi  a(DE-B1597)521354  a(OCoLC)1125187271  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQH541.15.M3bA55 2018 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a5772231 aAllen, T. F. H., eauthor.10aHierarchy :bPerspectives for Ecological Complexity /cThomas B. Starr, T. F. H. Allen. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b51 halftones, 28 line drawings, 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Nature of the Problem -- tPart I. A Theory for Medium Number Systems -- tPart II. Origins of Life as a Complex Medium Number System -- tPart III. Scale and Complex Systems -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough complexity surrounds us, its inherent uncertainty, ambiguity, and contradiction can at first make complex systems appear inscrutable. Ecosystems, for instance, are nonlinear, self-organizing, seemingly chaotic structures in which individuals interact both with each other and with the myriad biotic and abiotic components of their surroundings across geographies as well as spatial and temporal scales. In the face of such complexity, ecologists have long sought tools to streamline and aggregate information. Among them, in the 1980s, T. F. H. Allen and Thomas B. Starr implemented a burgeoning concept from business administration: hierarchy theory. Cutting-edge when Hierarchy was first published, their approach to unraveling complexity is now integrated into mainstream ecological thought. This thoroughly revised and expanded second edition of Hierarchy reflects the assimilation of hierarchy theory into ecological research, its successful application to the understanding of complex systems, and the many developments in thought since. Because hierarchies and levels are habitual parts of human thinking, hierarchy theory has proven to be the most intuitive and tractable vehicle for addressing complexity. By allowing researchers to look explicitly at only the entities and interconnections that are relevant to a specific research question, hierarchically informed data analysis has enabled a revolution in ecological understanding. With this new edition of Hierarchy, that revolution continues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aEcologyxMathematical models. 0aEcologyxMethodology. 0aEcologyxPhilosophy. 4acomplexity. 4aconstraint. 4aemergence. 4ahierarchy. 4aholon. 4alevels. 4amodel. 4anarrative. 4aobservation. 4ascale. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aStarr, Thomas B., eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226489711423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226489711.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles